This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it focuses on generating high-quality language descriptions. It also involves the use of generative adversarial networks (GANs) which are commonly used in natural language processing (NLP) tasks. 

The paper could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a novel approach for training GANs using policy gradient techniques. 

Additionally, the paper could be categorized under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it involves the use of machine learning techniques to generate language descriptions. 

The paper may also fall under cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as it involves the use of neural networks, which are a key component of GANs. 

Finally, the paper could be categorized under cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) as GANs are commonly used in image generation tasks, and the proposed approach involves ranking a collection of sentences, which could be seen as a form of image classification.
